{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564977"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:21:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:21:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17175"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17175"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.17,0.57,0.16,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9865"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69006"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9865"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17175"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54463"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"2264"},{"type":"tags","id":"2500"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23125"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69006"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of intermittent haemoptysis and persistent dry cough. She also reports episodes of facial flushing and diarrhoea occurring several times per week, and occasional wheeze. She has no chest pain, fever, night sweats, or weight loss. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never smoked and works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her face appears flushed. Chest examination reveals scattered wheeze with otherwise normal breath sounds. A chest radiograph shows a well-circumscribed hilar mass. CT chest demonstrates a 2.5 cm well-defined enhancing mass in the right main bronchus with no lymphadenopathy or metastases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mucoepidermoid carcinoma","Small cell lung cancer","Bronchial carcinoid tumour","Bronchial adenoma","Squamous cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents several classic features of bronchial carcinoid tumour: a young patient with haemoptysis, cough, and features of carcinoid syndrome (flushing, diarrhoea, and wheezing). The characteristic imaging findings show a well-circumscribed endobronchial mass. Bronchial carcinoid tumours are rare neuroendocrine tumours that typically occur in younger patients (mean age 45 years) and are not associated with smoking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchial carcinoid tumour\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the patient\u0027s age, presentation, and imaging findings. These tumours are typically slow-growing and have a good prognosis. They commonly present with haemoptysis due to their highly vascular nature and their location in the central airways. While carcinoid syndrome is rare in bronchial carcinoids (occurring in less than 5% of cases), it can occur due to serotonin secretion by the tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall cell lung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in older patients with a significant smoking history. It usually presents with systemic symptoms such as weight loss and tends to be more aggressive with early metastases. While it can produce paraneoplastic syndromes, carcinoid syndrome is not typically associated with SCLC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the lung is strongly associated with smoking and typically occurs in older patients. While it can present with haemoptysis, it usually appears as a more irregular mass with possible cavitation on imaging and does not cause carcinoid syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchial adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an outdated term that was previously used to describe several types of bronchial tumours, including carcinoid tumours. It is no longer used in current classification systems as it implies benign behaviour, which is not always the case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMucoepidermoid carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare tumour that can occur in the bronchi, but it typically presents with obstruction rather than haemoptysis as its primary symptom. It does not cause carcinoid syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bronchial carcinoid tumours typically present with recurrent haemoptysis and cough in young adults","Central bronchial carcinoid tumours appear as well-circumscribed endobronchial masses on CT chest","Carcinoid syndrome is rare in bronchial carcinoid tumours, occurring in less than 5% of cases","Carcinoid syndrome features include flushing, diarrhoea, and wheezing due to serotonin secretion"],"references":["Srirajaskanthan R, Marelli L, Karpathakis A, Toumpanakis C, Meyer T, Buscombe J, et al. Bronchial carcinoid tumours: Clinical features and management in a series of 45 patients. JCO. 2008 May 20;26(15_suppl):19076\u201319076."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54463"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17175"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54463"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T19:54:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T19:57:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9865"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69006"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understan